explanation:
For determining whether any part of OS_ObjectIdFinalizeDelete is unreachable the analyzer must know:

- OS_SUCCESS
  - The constant used in the conditional checks. Needed to know its value/range and whether callers can ever pass this value so that either branch could be taken.

- OS_OBJECT_ID_UNDEFINED
  - The value assigned in the success branch. Needed to ensure the assignment isn't a macro with side effects or an alias that could affect reachability analysis.

- OS_EVENT_RESOURCE_DELETED
  - The event passed to OS_NotifyEvent in the success-only branch. Needed to confirm it is a regular constant and does not expand to something that affects control flow (e.g. triggers compile-time removal).

- osal_id_t
  - The typedef of final_id. Required to check for any unusual type semantics or implicit conversions that could affect evaluation/optimizations and potential reachability conclusions.

- OS_object_token_t (definition, including member obj_id)
  - The token structure and the obj_id member are read/used in both branches. Needed to ensure accesses are valid and to determine if token->obj_id is a compile-time constant or otherwise affects whether the else branch can ever be executed.

- OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish (definition/implementation)
  - This function is called unconditionally before the second conditional and could perform non-local control flow (longjmp, exit, noreturn) which would make code after it unreachable. Its body/signature is required to rule that out.

- OS_NotifyEvent (definition/implementation)
  - Likewise, this is called only in the success branch; if it performed non-local control flow the branch semantics could differ. Need to know it does not force early termination.

- All callers of OS_ObjectIdFinalizeDelete (OS_BinSemDelete, OS_CondVarDelete, OS_CountSemDelete, OS_DirectoryClose, OS_close, OS_rmfs, OS_ModuleUnload, OS_MutSemDelete, OS_QueueDelete, OS_TaskDelete, OS_TaskExit, OS_TimeBaseDelete, OS_TimerDelete)
  - To prove whether either branch is reachable from the whole program, the analyzer must inspect every call site to see what operation_status values are passed (constants, values calculated from other functions, or always a fixed value). If every caller always passes a single value (e.g. always OS_SUCCESS), the opposite branch would be unreachable. Thus the callers' implementations (or at least the expressions/values they pass as operation_status) are required.

Note: The listed symbols are the minimal set required to determine if any of the conditional branches (and the OS_NotifyEvent call) can never be executed or if code after OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish is rendered unreachable by that callee. Additional deep symbols (e.g., functions that compute the status inside the callers) may be needed when inspecting each caller's logic, but the callers themselves are the next-level symbols required for that analysis.
